The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 UTV price band at Rs 115-130 

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 

 Mumbai, Feb. 9: UTV Software Communications, a media and entertainment company, has fixed the price band for its initial public offering (IPO) at Rs 115-130 per share. UTV is planning a public issue of 69.99 lakh shares through the 100 per cent book building route. 

 The offering will part-finance UTV?s expansion plans. At the upper end of the price band, the company will mobilise Rs 91 crore and at the lower end Rs 80.5 crore.

 The lead manager to the issue is Enam Financial Consultants, which will be assisted by IL amp;FS Investsmart. The issue will be open between February 21 and 25. 

 The IPO comprises fresh equity of 4,500,000 shares and offer for sale of 2,499,950 equity shares by CDPQ, a Canadian private equity investor. 

 The issue has 349,950 shares reserved for employees and a net issue to public of 6,650,000. The net issue to public would constitute 34.11 per cent of the fully diluted post-issue paid-up capital of the company. 

 Of the net issue to public, up to 50 per cent will go to qualified institutional buyers on a discretionary basis, while not less than 25 per cent will be allocated to non-institutional investors and not less than 25 per cent will go to retail investors on a proportionate basis

 According to UTV, the proceeds from the IPO will be used to improve its production facility and office infrastructure, investment in the ?Kids Channel? (Hungama TV) project, funding of SFX amp; post-production expansion, investment in movie production and distribution initiatives and general corporate purposes. The roadshows for the issue will be kicked off from Mumbai on February 14, followed by Delhi and Ahmedabad. 

 UTV was set up in 1990 and has since focused on being an integrated entertainment company with interest in television content production and airtime sales, movie production and distribution, dubbing, ad film making and post-production services by concentrating on television content and movie production. 

 A Ficci-Ernst amp; Young report on the domestic entertainment industry has said that last year, the industry continued to out-perform the economy and grew 15 per cent to an estimated Rs 19,200 crore. 




